ub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=valquisssilverpalm>Valquiss Silverpalm</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 798<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/3/03 12:04 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3968.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   You know, I feel bad for the raiding guilds</span><hr size=1> Hi all.  This post might end up sounding sarcastic at times, but it really isn't meant to be.  After reading a couple of posts recently, and considering them in combination, I have come to understand far better the pressures faced by raiding guilds striving for end-game content, and I have come to believe that they have been indirectly shafted by some really bad design in EQ.<br>
<br>
First, I was thinking about that thread about Resolution with bad karma in the title or something.  The point was that guests on a Reso raid were asked to leave once members showed up to clear room on the 72-person raid, which would end up being who got flagged for the PoP kill.  That was an eye-opener for me.  I always knew raids got big in the end, but Resolution needing to *fill* the 72-person roster?  Wow.  I'm not a complete noob or anything, and I've been on and led some fair-sized planar raids.  But I guess always figured that even though huge raids do happen, skilled and well-equiped raiders can still raid in 30-40 person groups and continue to progress that way, even if they move in smaller steps than a gigantic raid force. Looks like I was wrong.<br>
<br>
Second, I was reading that thread about F&amp;F where they were being accused of backing down from their stance on Ebayers in order to grow.  The idea being that they now either need to grow or die.  I don't have a clue if that last part is at all true and I'm going to omit my feelings about the first part.  The point is, in light of the first revelation about what kind of raid force it takes to approach the end game, I can begin to understand how and why a raiding guild would end up compromising on just about any standard when faced with that obstacle.  And that sucks.<br>
<br>
I did some quick math.  I figure that a well-organized, seriously hardcore raiding guild might manage to field a 72-character raid force with a roster of about 80 players, assuming a fair number of them are duo-boxing (or more) and there are very few vacations from EQ in there and they all manage to play at very regular times.  A less-organized, serious raiding guild might need as many as 120 players in its roster to field a 72-character force regularly, especially if it includes players who aren't willing to raid 6-7 nights a week.  Am I in the right ballpark there folks?  I really don't know, but for now I'm proceeding on the assumption that to continue progressing and advancing steadily a serious raiding guild needs about 80-120 people on its roster.<br>
<br>
All I can say to that is Holy Shit!  Even if I've over-estimated and it's more like 60-90, still, Holy Shit!<br>
<br>
We like to talk about how different priorities can co-exist in the same guild, and how a guild might roleplay and still raid, or raid and still roleplay, etc.  But all I can think of is that one of the things I value most about a guild is when I can say I am honestly proud to be associated with everyone else who wears that tag.  Not just in terms of their raiding skill, but in all aspects of their personalities.  If I can't say that I just won't wear the guild tag.  And now I thinking about raiding guilds....  This isn't meant to imply that raiders are any less worthy than anyone else, but I can't imagine *any* group of 80-120 (or even 60-90) people I'd care to associate myself with that way.  When was the last time you can remember going out to the movies with 80 of your closest friends?  It just isn't part of human nature to be at all close to that many people at a time.<br>
<br>
So it seems to me raiding guilds end up in a situation where they are reduced to considering one and only one thing when it comes to recruiting new members, and that's raiding ability.  With perhaps a secondary emphesis on making sure the person they add to the guild isn't such a total tool as to offend the rest of the guild and mess up doing anything co-operatively.  And again, that's sad.<br>
<br>
I think EQ is moving in the right direction with the LDoN expansion, and even though we think they are moving in a new direction there I would claim, rather, they are exploring on a micro level what they have already done on a macro level with PoP.  They *did* effectively limit the effective encounter force for a lot of PoP, just they limited it so high (72) we tend not to notice.  But it is at least limited.  Otherwise we might be seeing raid forces over 100 strong.<br>
<br>
I remember when F&amp;F had a distinctive flavour on FV.  I remember when Resolution had the same.  Now I can't even tell them apart, in membership, attitude, or philosophy.  I'm sorry to anyone who has a serious grudge and resents being compared to the opposing camp, but I really can't tell the difference.  I just can't.  And I wonder what it might be like if raiding encounters were similarly limited to, say, 36 characters.  Maybe then these top end guilds wouldn't be forced to grow or die.  Maybe then they might retain a tight core of people who worked together and shared some ideals and ideas beyond just getting to end-game content.  Maybe....  I don't know.  I just wanted to point this all out.<br>
<br>
Limiting the number of people who can attempt any one thing together at once is good for the game.  At every level.  It gives us more ability to choose who we are going to associate with without the massive pressure of raising a huge force when needed.  I'm sure I'll have people disagree, but that's the way I see it.  I respect what the end-game raiders are doing, and where they are taking their own quests, but I'm sorry for what they've had to give up along the way.  And I wish they didn't have to.<br>
<br>
Take care,<br>
Valquiss <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=lothor2>Lothor2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 113<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/3/03 12:40 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3968.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: You know, I feel bad for the raiding guilds</span><hr size=1> maybe reso didnt feel like making the regearing of the 30-50 new apps a priority and planar progression with what they had on top... <br>
